    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{1)}$ ___(1 point)___. Consider a SISO setting, with no fading. Consider that the maximum possible rate (i.e., the capacity) is equal to $3$ bpcu. What is the minimum SNR required to achieve this rate?\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4113660-6d19-4b7c-b6b9-02ab3c3b8a7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Answer:**\n",
    "\n",
    "The capacity formula for a SISO channel without fading is given by the **Shannon capacity** equation:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "C = \\log_2(1 + \\text{SNR})\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Given $C = 3 \\, \\text{bpcu}$, solve for SNR:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "3 = \\log_2(1 + \\text{SNR})\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Convert to linear form:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "1 + \\text{SNR} = 2^3 = 8\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, the minimum SNR required is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\n",
    "\\text{SNR} = 8 - 1 = 7\n",
    "$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Final Answer:** The minimum SNR required is **7** (or **8.45 dB** if expressed in dB)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8b1ddcd1-3c8b-41db-9975-e4bdf20893d1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{2)}$ ___(1 point)___. Consider a SISO fading channel with no CSIT. Imagine that we are not happy with a\n",
    "probability of error $P_{\\text{err}} \\approx (SNR)^{−1}$. Suggest various ways we can decrease this down to $P_{\\text{err}} \\approx (SNR)^{−4}$\n",
    "."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f1efc62f-489a-4fb2-a63f-5ecfd5c36b7f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "To achieve $P_{\\text{err}} \\approx \\text{SNR}^{-4}$, increase diversity using:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Time Diversity:** Transmit over multiple independent time slots (e.g., through retransmissions or coding).  \n",
    "2. **Frequency Diversity:** Use multiple independent frequency channels (e.g., OFDM).  \n",
    "3. **Spatial Diversity:** Employ multiple antennas (e.g., MISO, SIMO) or space-time coding (e.g., Alamouti).  \n",
    "4. **Error-Correcting Codes:** Apply powerful FEC codes (e.g., LDPC, turbo codes)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0454ea2c-d0d1-4769-b06d-25ebc00010a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{3)}$ ___(1 point)___. What are some of the advantages of **MISO** vs. **SIMO**?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d21b09f0-b936-4573-bb56-2ec90077f54e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "- **Advantages of MISO over SIMO:**  \n",
    "  1. **Beamforming gain:** MISO enables the transmitter to perform **beamforming**, focusing the signal in the direction of the receiver, improving SNR and range.  \n",
    "  2. **Power efficiency:** MISO can distribute transmission power across multiple antennas, reducing overall energy consumption while maintaining performance.  \n",
    "  3. **Interference control:** In multi-user scenarios, MISO allows for **precoding** to mitigate interference between users.  \n",
    "\n",
    "- **SIMO advantage:** SIMO provides **receive diversity** without requiring complex transmission strategies, which is simpler to implement but lacks beamforming capabilities."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4e88b624-1b3b-438b-a846-2825ef0ebd05",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{4)}$ ___(1 point)___. In multi-user **MISO** settings, describe some of the advantages and some of the disadvantages of matched filtering vs. zero forcing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "02ab582f-33ec-43ac-a49a-801c023f9adf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "- **Matched Filtering:**  \n",
    "  - **Advantages:** Simple to implement, low computational complexity, maximizes signal power at each user.  \n",
    "  - **Disadvantages:** Does not effectively handle inter-user interference, especially in high-user scenarios.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Zero Forcing (ZF):**  \n",
    "  - **Advantages:** Eliminates inter-user interference by orthogonalizing users' signals.  \n",
    "  - **Disadvantages:** Higher computational complexity and sensitivity to noise amplification in low-SNR conditions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "38a84aca-9da9-40ad-aa69-9b055abb2be3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{5)}$ ___(1 point)___. Provide a real-life scenario that entails an AWGN channel and one that entails fast fading."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2741a9d2-b091-49d7-b90e-9c87a556ad24",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "- **AWGN Channel:** Communication between two stationary ground stations with minimal interference and obstacles (e.g., satellite-to-ground communication in clear weather).  \n",
    "- **Fast Fading Channel:** Communication in a mobile environment, such as between a moving car and a base station, where rapid changes in the channel occur due to mobility and multipath effects."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68105fcc-5805-42db-b797-4456bb5dc1f0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{6)}$ ___(1 point)___. What is the main reason for using OFDM? (1 line)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa47afc1-1dd1-4017-9cfe-4992db2017c2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "The main reason for using **OFDM** is to convert a **frequency-selective fading** channel into multiple **flat-fading** subchannels, simplifying equalization and improving data transmission over broadband channels."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7ebf6367-881e-4849-ac99-0e57fbdfc27e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{7)}$ ___(1 point)___. What is the complication that prevents interference alignment from being widely used in practice? (1 line)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d823c17b-9a4e-4b31-a447-f865ef815d0f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "The main complication is the requirement for **perfect and global channel state information (CSI)** at all transmitters, which is difficult to achieve due to **feedback delays**, **channel estimation errors**, and **dynamic channel conditions**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "58307a8d-3670-4847-89ee-849fd5db9bf2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{8)}$ ___(1 point)___. What does channel hardening mean in Massive **MIMO**? (1-2 lines)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c2360910-52ce-433b-b741-2ea4acae932f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "**Channel hardening** in Massive MIMO refers to the phenomenon where the effective channel gain becomes nearly **deterministic** as the number of antennas increases, reducing the impact of small-scale fading and improving **link reliability**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a7c56479-e4a1-4273-b359-785837d0b908",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{9)}$ ___(1 point)___. What does favorable propagation mean in Massive MIMO and what does it imply for receiver and transmitter design? (2-3 lines)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "893f7d86-4678-4b5e-b190-f8fd525dacf7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "**Favorable propagation** in Massive MIMO refers to the condition where the channel vectors between different users are **nearly orthogonal**. This implies:\n",
    "- **Simpler receiver design** with minimal interference, allowing linear detectors like **ZF** or **MMSE** to perform well.  \n",
    "- **Simpler transmitter design** with efficient **spatial multiplexing** and **precoding**, improving system capacity and user separation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "54ce5c48-71ef-4548-8f46-53ae84b13dc3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{10)}$ ___(1 point)___. How would Cell-Free Massive MIMO allow us to reduce energy consumption? (1 line)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "63bf5851-008e-4750-aa4d-d11a01e6f9c8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "Cell-Free Massive MIMO reduces energy consumption by using **distributed antennas** closer to users, which lowers path loss and enables **low-power beamforming** with improved energy efficiency."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5a408dcb-3437-4bee-b390-e6275e4c5db0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{11)}$ ___(1 point)___. In a single-user MIMO channel, how much diversity gain would we be able to get if we employed a transmitter with 4 transmit antennas and a receiver with 2 receive antennas?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4173a1c2-cc2d-4e28-932e-081680365350",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "The **diversity gain** in a **single-user MIMO** channel is given by:\n",
    "\n",
    "$\\text{Diversity gain} = N_t \\cdot N_r$ Where:\n",
    "- $N_t = 4$ (transmit antennas),\n",
    "- $N_r = 2$ (receive antennas).\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, the **diversity gain** is:\n",
    "$\\text{Diversity gain} = 4 \\cdot 2 = \\boxed{ 8 }$\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f1a30605-9527-4548-aa90-6d3a124e83c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{12)}$ ___(1 point)___. In a single-user MISO channel, how much multiplexing gain would we be able to get if we employed a transmitter with 2 transmit antennas?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dc69407b-3d28-4f75-9d99-2bf9c9665fe4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "In a **single-user MISO** channel, **multiplexing gain** refers to the maximum number of independent data streams that can be transmitted simultaneously.\n",
    "\n",
    "- With **2 transmit antennas** and **1 receive antenna**, the system can only transmit **1 spatial stream**, since there is only **1 receive antenna** to distinguish and decode the streams.\n",
    "  \n",
    "Thus, the **multiplexing gain** is **1**, even with multiple transmit antennas."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "29d749e2-b470-4bc5-90db-f00cc15b1a08",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{13)}$ ___(1 point)___. Consider a SISO fading channel with coherence time equal to $T_c = 10$ milli-seconds.\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine that our boss imposes a delay constraint of $50$ms.\n",
    "- What type of diversity do we expect to get here: time diversity or spatial diversity?\n",
    "- What is the maximal such diversity?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "640c57c6-942f-4adc-85ee-36d720134eb1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "- **Type of Diversity:**  \n",
    "  **Time diversity** – Since it's a SISO (Single Input Single Output) channel, there are no multiple antennas to provide spatial diversity. However, multiple independent channel realizations can occur within the allowed delay period, enabling time diversity.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Maximal Time Diversity:**  \n",
    "  The number of independent channel realizations within the delay constraint is:  $\\text{Max time diversity} = \\frac{\\text{Delay constraint}}{T_c} = \\frac{50 \\, \\text{ms}}{10 \\, \\text{ms}} = \\boxed{ 5 }$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aee2639f-f9c6-4915-8e37-8da3e283ca29",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{14)}$ ___(1 point)___. Consider communication over a quasi-static $2 \\times 1$ **MISO** fading channel. Assume that you must draw symbols from 16-QAM.\n",
    "- What is the diversity and the rate (in bpcu) given by the Alamouti code? Justify your answer."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "036b526b-87b4-4487-9836-f7aaf65618c3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "1. **Diversity:**  \n",
    "   The **Alamouti code** is a **space-time block code** for a **2 × 1 MISO** system. It provides full **diversity gain**, which is equal to the product of transmit and receive antennas:\n",
    "$\\text{Diversity gain} = N_t \\cdot N_r = 2 \\cdot 1 = \\boxed{2}$\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **Rate (in bpcu):**  \n",
    "   The **rate** of a code is given by:\n",
    "$R = \\frac{\\text{Number of information symbols per codeword}}{\\text{Number of time slots}}$\n",
    "\n",
    "   - In the Alamouti code, 2 information symbols are transmitted over **2 time slots**.\n",
    "   - Since 16-QAM encodes **4 bits per symbol**, the rate is:\n",
    "$R = \\frac{2 \\cdot 4 \\, \\text{bits}}{2 \\, \\text{time slots}} = \\boxed{ 4 \\, \\text{bpcu}}$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e436249-68f9-4350-9636-8b1d1eec69a2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "$\\color{orange} \\large \\textbf{15)}$ ___(3 points)___. In the context of various strategies, answer if each of the following statements are true or false, justifying briefly your answers.\n",
    "- In a **MISO** channel, we can get transmitter beamforming gain even without CSIT.\n",
    "- A base station equipped with 5 antennas in the downlink, can simultaneously serve up to 5 users (single receive antenna each).\n",
    "- A base station equipped with 5 antennas in the downlink, can simultaneously serve up to 10 users (two receive antennas each).\n",
    "- A base station equipped with 4 antennas in the downlink, can simultaneously serve up to 2 users (two receive antennas each).\n",
    "- Line of sight channels are detrimental for spatial multiplexing in both single-user and multiuser **MIMO**.\n",
    "- For a **MIMO** receiver using spatial multiplexing, the complexity of ZF receiver is more than the complexity of the maximum-likelihood receiver.\n",
    "- CSIT is easier to obtain than CSIR.\n",
    "- CSIT is of cardinal importance in multi-user **MIMO**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "00ede50f-c123-4409-9982-feda0e5c932a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **In a MISO channel, we can get transmitter beamforming gain even without CSIT:**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ False }}$ – Beamforming requires **channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT)** to direct the signal towards the receiver effectively.\n",
    "2. **A base station with 5 antennas can simultaneously serve up to 5 users (single antenna each):**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ True }}$ – With **5 antennas**, the base station can form **5 spatial streams**, allowing it to serve up to **5 single-antenna users** simultaneously through spatial multiplexing.\n",
    "3. **A base station with 5 antennas can simultaneously serve up to 10 users (two antennas each):**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ False }}$ – The base station can support a maximum of **5 spatial streams**, so it cannot serve **10 users** simultaneously, even if each user has two antennas.\n",
    "4. **A base station with 4 antennas can simultaneously serve up to 2 users (two antennas each):**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ True }}$ – The base station can support **4 spatial streams**. Two users with **2 antennas each** can be served if the channel supports full spatial rank.\n",
    "5. **Line of sight channels are detrimental for spatial multiplexing in both single-user and multi-user MIMO:**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ True }}$ – In line-of-sight (LOS) channels, **high correlation** between antenna signals can limit the spatial multiplexing gain due to poor channel rank.\n",
    "6. **For a MIMO receiver using spatial multiplexing, the complexity of a ZF receiver is more than the complexity of a maximum-likelihood receiver:**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ False }}$ – **Zero-forcing (ZF)** has lower complexity than **maximum-likelihood (ML)**, which involves exhaustive search over all possible transmitted symbol combinations.\n",
    "7. **CSIT is easier to obtain than CSIR:**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ False }}$ – **Channel state information at the receiver (CSIR)** is naturally obtained through pilot signals. **CSIT** requires feedback from the receiver, which introduces additional complexity and latency.\n",
    "8. **CSIT is of cardinal importance in multi-user MIMO:**  \n",
    "   $\\boxed{\\text{ True }}$ – CSIT enables **precoding** and **interference management** in multi-user MIMO, which are crucial for efficiently serving multiple users simultaneously."
   ]
  },
  {
